<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!DOCTYPE plist PUBLIC "-//Apple//DTD PLIST 1.0//EN" "http://www.apple.com/DTDs/PropertyList-1.0.dtd">
<!--
  Entitlements for the Hardened Runtime. Referenced by
  `bundle.macOS.entitlements` in tauri.conf.json.

  Hardened Runtime is mandatory for notarization, and it is NOT free: it
  re-imposes restrictions that an unhardened ad-hoc build never had. Each key
  below exists because something breaks without it.

  com.apple.security.device.audio-input
    Under Hardened Runtime the microphone is gated by this entitlement in
    addition to NSMicrophoneUsageDescription. Without it the app is denied the
    mic — reintroducing, by a different mechanism, exactly the "force-quits when
    I try to talk" bug that v0.2.1 fixed by adding the purpose string. This is
    the single most load-bearing line in this file.

  com.apple.security.cs.disable-library-validation
    Hardened Runtime turns on library validation, which refuses to load a dylib
    unless it is signed by the same Team ID as the host binary (or is an Apple
    platform binary). The Intel build bundles Microsoft's libonnxruntime into
    Contents/Frameworks; the tauri bundler signs it with our identity, so under a
    real Developer ID this would validate. But an AD-HOC signature carries no
    Team ID, so an ad-hoc hardened build cannot validate its own bundled dylib.
    Rather than have the Intel build work only when signed with a certificate we
    do not yet own, disable library validation. Revisit once Developer ID
    signing lands and the Intel dmg has actually been launched on Intel hardware:
    if it loads with this removed, remove it.

  NOT included, deliberately:
    com.apple.security.cs.allow-jit / allow-unsigned-executable-memory —
    llama.cpp's Metal path compiles shaders through the out-of-process Metal
    compiler service, not in-process JIT, and ONNX Runtime's CoreML EP does the
    same. Neither should need executable-memory entitlements. If a hardened
    build ever crashes inside llama.cpp or ORT with EXC_BAD_ACCESS on first
    inference, this is the first thing to try — but do not add it speculatively;
    each entitlement widens the attack surface of a local-first app.

  There is no entitlement for Accessibility or Input Monitoring. Those are TCC
  services granted from System Settings, not code-signing capabilities.
-->
<plist version="1.0">
  <dict>
    <key>com.apple.security.device.audio-input</key>
    <true/>
    <key>com.apple.security.cs.disable-library-validation</key>
    <true/>
  </dict>
</plist>
